{"parse":{"title":"Georgia House Bill 51","pageid":53804354,"revid":798623703,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>House Bill 51</b> (full title: <b>Postsecondary institutions; reporting and investigation of certain crimes by officials and employees; provide manner</b>) is a bill introduced into the <a href=\"/wiki/Georgia_House_of_Representatives\" title=\"Georgia House of Representatives\">Georgia House of Representatives</a> which would limit the ability of college campuses in <a href=\"/wiki/Georgia_(U.S._state)\" title=\"Georgia (U.S. state)\">Georgia</a> to investigate alleged <a href=\"/wiki/Sex_crime\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sex crime\">sex crimes</a> committed on campus.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> For example, it would effectively sidestep the common university practice of holding so-called \"<a href=\"/wiki/Title_IX\" title=\"Title IX\">Title IX</a> hearings\" to decide whether to discipline a student accused of sexual assault.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Instead, the bill would require some university employees to report possible felonies to law enforcement. The bill was introduced by Representative <a href=\"/wiki/Earl_Ehrhart\" title=\"Earl Ehrhart\">Earl Ehrhart</a> (R-<a href=\"/wiki/Powder_Springs\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Powder Springs\">Powder Springs</a>) on January 11, 2017,<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and was passed by the House of Representatives on March 1, 2017, in a 115-55 vote.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> On March 24, the Georgia State Senate Judiciary Committee tabled the bill,<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> On March 28, Ehrhart replaced a part of Senate Bill 71 that pertained to <a href=\"/wiki/Health_savings_account\" title=\"Health savings account\">health savings accounts</a> with language from House Bill 51 in an effort to get it passed.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Nevertheless, this bill, like HB51, failed to receive final approval before the state legislature ended its work for the year. However, it can still be considered for passage in next year's session.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Georgia_House_Bill_51&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Bauer-Wolf, Jeremy (11 April 2017). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/04/11/controversial-georgia-sexual-assault-bill-prompts-debate-reporting\">\"Who Should Investigate Sexual Assaults?\"</a>. <i>Inside Higher Ed</i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Inside+Higher+Ed&amp;rft.atitle=Who+Should+Investigate+Sexual+Assaults%3F&amp;rft.date=2017-04-11&amp;rft.aulast=Bauer-Wolf&amp;rft.aufirst=Jeremy&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.insidehighered.com%2Fnews%2F2017%2F04%2F11%2Fcontroversial-georgia-sexual-assault-bill-prompts-debate-reporting&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGeorgia+House+Bill+51\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><s